{{Infobox organization |name= Home Radio Frequency Working Group |image= File:HomeRF Working Group logo.gif |formation= {{Start date |1998}} |extinction= {{End date |2003}} |type= Industry consortium }}
'''HomeRF''' was a [[wireless networking]] specification for home devices. It was developed in 1998 by the Home Radio Frequency Working Group, a consortium of mobile wireless companies that included [[Proxim Wireless]], [[Intel]], [[Siemens AG]], [[Motorola]], [[Philips]] and more than 100 other companies.<ref name="caswell">{{cite web |title= HomeRF Archives |author= Wayne Caswell |date= November 17, 2010 |url= http://www.cazitech.com/HomeRF_Archives.htm |accessdate= July 16, 2011 }}</ref>
The group was disbanded in January 2003 after other wireless networks became accessible to home users and [[Microsoft]] began including support for them in its [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]] [[operating system]]s. As a result, HomeRF fell into obsolescence.
==Description== Initially called Shared Wireless Access Protocol (SWAP) and later just HomeRF, this open specification allowed PCs, peripherals, cordless phones and other consumer devices to share and communicate voice and data in and around the home without the complication and expense of running new wires. HomeRF combined several wireless technologies in the [[ISM band|2.4&nbsp;GHz ISM band]], including [[IEEE 802.11 FH]] (the frequency-hopping version of wireless data networking) and [[DECT]] (the most prevalent digital cordless telephony standard in the world) to meet the unique home networking requirements for security, [[quality of service]] (QoS) and interference immunity—issues that still plagued [[Wi-Fi]] (802.11b and g).{{Citation needed |date= September 2013 }}
HomeRF used [[frequency hopping]] [[spread spectrum]] (FHSS) in the 2.4 [[GHz]] frequency band and in theory could achieve a maximum of 10 Mbit/s throughput; its nodes could travel within a 50-meter range of a [[wireless access point]] while remaining connected to the [[personal area network]] (PAN). Several standards and working groups focused on wireless networking technology in [[radio frequency]] (RF). Other standards include the popular [[IEEE 802.11]] family, [[IEEE 802.16]], and [[Bluetooth]].
[[Proxim Wireless]] was the only supplier of HomeRF chipsets, and since Proxim also made end products, other manufacturers complained that they had to buy components from their competitor. The fact that our group didn't address that conflict led to the eventual downfall of HomeRF, which occurred during an economic recession when companies already struggled to justify duplicate engineering and marketing efforts - for HomeRF, 802.11 and Bluetooth. The fact that HomeRF was developed by a consortium and not an official standards body also put it at a disadvantage against Wi-Fi and its IEEE 802.11 standard.{{Citation needed |date= September 2013 }}
AT&T joined the group because HomeRF was designed for high-speed broadband services and the need to support PCs, phones, stereos and televisions; but last-mile deployment occurred more slowly than expected and with slower speeds. So it was natural that the home networking market focused more on multi-PC households sharing Internet connections for email and browsing than on integrating phone and entertainment services into a broadband service bundle. As a result, the original promoter companies gradually started pulling out of the group rather than supporting multiple standards. They included IBM, Hewlett-Packard, Compaq, Microsoft, and lastly Intel. That left only companies like Motorola, National Semiconductor, Proxim, and Siemens. Even Proxim started pulling away when negative media surrounding HomeRF started affecting its core data networking business, and that left Siemens to do the work of integrating voice, data and video. Siemens was willing to go it alone with HomeRF technology but was concerned by growing uncertainties in the cordless phone market, including mobile phone as home phone, [[VoIP]] over Wi-Fi, and 5&nbsp;GHz vs. 2.4&nbsp;GHz. When Siemens eventually got out of the cordless phone market, it was the final nail in the HomeRF coffin.{{Citation needed |date= September 2013 }}
HomeRF received some success because of its low cost and ease of installation.<ref>{{cite book |author1= [[Ted Coombs]] |author2= Roderico Deleon |title= Basic Home Networking |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=BO3hc1r_tC0C |date= July 24, 2002 |pages= 12–14 |publisher= Cengage Learning |isbn=978-0-7668-6180-0 }}</ref> By September 2000, some confusion came from the "home" in the name, leading some to associate HomeRF with [[home network]]s, using other technologies such as [[IEEE 802.11b]] for businesses.<ref>{{Cite news|title=HomeRF vs. 802.11b |author=Joanie Wexler |work=Network World Wireless in the Enterprise Newsletter |publisher=Network World Fusion |date=September 25, 2000 |url=http://www.networkworld.com/newsletters/wireless/2000/0925wire1.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080120191922/http://www.networkworld.com/newsletters/wireless/2000/0925wire1.html |dead-url=yes |archive-date=January 20, 2008 |accessdate=September 14, 2013 }}</ref> A [[digital media receiver]] for audio was marketed under the name "Motorola SimpleFi" that used HomeRF.<ref>{{Cite news |title= Motorola Simplefi review |work= CNet |date= August 16, 2002 |url= http://reviews.cnet.com/digital-audio-receivers-dars/motorola-simplefi/4505-6470_7-9050945.html |accessdate= September 14, 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title= Simplefi Your Digital Music |work= PC Magazine |author= Bill Howard |date= March 13, 2002 |url= https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,4785,00.asp |accessdate= September 14, 2013 }}</ref> In March 2001, Intel announced they would not support further development of HomeRF technology for its Anypoint line.<ref>{{Cite news |title= The Ripple Effect: How Intel's Choice to Support 802.11b is Affecting the Home Networking Market |work= Home Networks Newsletter |volume=3 |number=4 |pages= 9–10 |date= April 2001 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=SCEor912ICwC&pg=PA9 }}</ref> The group promoting 802.11 technology, the [[Wi-Fi Alliance|Wireless Ethernet Compatibility Alliance]] (WECA) changed their name to the Wi-Fi Alliance in 2002, as the [[Wi-Fi]] brand became popular.<ref>{{Cite news |title= Wi-Fi5, We Hardly Knew Ye |author= Eric Griffith |work= 802.11 Planet |date= July 17, 2002 |url= http://www.80211-planet.com/news/article.php/1428541 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20021207042030/http://www.80211-planet.com/news/article.php/1428541 |archivedate= December 7, 2002 |accessdate= September 14, 2013 }}</ref>
The fact that WECA members lobbied the [[FCC]] for two years, which was effective in delaying the approval of wideband frequency-hopping, helped 802.11b catch up and gain an insurmountable lead in the market, which was then extended with 802.11g. The use of [[OFDM]] in 802.11a and .11g solved many of the RF interference problems of .11b. [[Wi-Fi Protected Access|WPA]] and [[802.11x]] also improved security over [[Wired Equivalent Privacy|WEP]] encryption, which was especially important in the corporate world.{{Citation needed |date= September 2013 }}
By January 2003 the Home Radio Frequency Working Group had disbanded.<ref>{{Cite news |title= HomeRF Working Group Calls it Quits |author= Clint Boulton |date= January 8, 2003 |work= Internet News |url= http://www.internetnews.com/wireless/article.php/1566311/HomeRF+Working+Group+Calls+it+Quits.htm |accessdate= September 14, 2013 }}</ref> Archives of the HomeRF Working Group are maintained by Palo Wireless and Wayne Caswell.<ref name="caswell" /><ref name="palo">{{Cite web|title=HomeRF Resource Center Contents |author=Eamon Myers |url=http://www.palowireless.com/homerf/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010614110309/http://www.palowireless.com/homerf/ |dead-url=yes |archive-date=June 14, 2001 |accessdate=September 14, 2013 }}</ref>
