{{About|the W49 nuclear warhead|Astronomical region|Westerhout 49}}
The '''W49''' was an American [[Thermonuclear weapon|thermonuclear warhead]], used on the [[PGM-17 Thor|Thor]], [[Atlas (missile)|Atlas]], [[Jupiter (missile)|Jupiter]], and [[Titan I]] ballistic missile systems.  W49 warheads were manufactured starting in 1958 and were in service until 1963, with a few warheads being retained until 1975.

The W49 has been described as a design derivative of the [[B28 nuclear bomb]] nuclear warhead design. It was {{convert|20|in|cm|0}} in diameter and {{convert|54|to|58|in|cm|0}} long depending on model, weighing {{convert|1640|to|1680|lb|0}}, and had a design yield of 1.44 [[TNT equivalent|megatons]].

